, like deleting and cleaning directories, and working with Jar files.\\\\n\\\\nHowever, it seems that some methods remain uncovered, such as `deleteRecursivelyQuietlyEvenIfInsecure(DirectoryStream)` and `cleanRecursively(Path/SDS/SDS, path)`. I think it could be helpful to test how `Files2.deleteRecursivelyQuietlyEvenIfInsecure(DirectoryStream)` behaves, especially since it reports stats while keeping the directory open. This involves combining existing tested features, but it may tread into untested territory.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering quiet secure tests**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about testing the quiet secure method to see if a nonexistent path returns zero stats instead of throwing an exception. There are existing tests for quiet paths, but those focus on nonexistent paths at the end of the directory. It’s interesting to consider how this might differ when applied to secure paths. It seems like a valuable test, but I want to make sure it aligns with the existing testing framework.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Testing image metadata**\\\\n\\\\nI need to test under the native image with the generated metadata. It's important to run checks afterward. However, I'm wondering if the existing source has a placeholder that's causing coverage issues. So, it seems the build might involve both factors. Alright, I think it's time to edit and see how we can address this!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_MkbDfu39pmTbHvd9h1EcKvbI|fc_03f95c4537ff46f30169f3994dcacc81a294bff34b5d70c01c\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/io.smallrye.common/smallrye-common-io/2.16.0/src/test/java/io_smallrye_common/smallrye_common_io/SmallryeCommonIoTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"    @Test\\n    void directoryStreamDeleteRemovesEntriesWithoutDeletingOpenedDirectory() throws IOException {\\n        Path root = newWorkspace(\\\"delete-stream-root\\\");\\n        Path nested = 